%N A007531 a(n) = n*(n-1)*(n-2) (or n!/(n-3)!).
%C A007531 _Ed Pegg Jr_ conjectures that n^3 - n = k! has a solution if and only if n is 2, 3, 5 or 9 (when k is 3, 4, 5 and 6).
%C A007531 Three-dimensional promic (or oblong) numbers, cf. A002378. - _Alexandre Wajnberg_, Dec 29 2005
%C A007531 Doubled first differences of tritriangular numbers A050534(n) = (1/8)n(n + 1)(n - 1)(n - 2). a(n) = 2*(A050534(n+1) - A050534(n)). - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Apr 11 2006
%C A007531 If Y is a 4-subset of an n-set X then, for n >= 6, a(n-4) is the number of (n-5)-subsets of X having exactly two elements in common with Y. - _Milan Janjic_, Dec 28 2007
%C A007531 Convolution of A005843 with A008585. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 07 2009
%C A007531 a(n) = A000578(n) - A000567(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Sep 18 2009
%C A007531 For n > 3: a(n) = A173333(n, n-3). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 19 2010
%C A007531 Let H be the n X n Hilbert matrix H(i, j) = 1/(i+j-1) for 1 <= i, j <= n. Let B be the inverse matrix of H. The sum of the elements in row 2 of B equals (-1)^n a(n+1). - _T. D. Noe_, May 01 2011
%C A007531 a(n) equals 2^(n-1) times the coefficient of log(3) in 2F1(n-2, n-2, n, -2). - _John M. Campbell_, Jul 16 2011
%C A007531 For n > 2 a(n) = 1/(Integral_{x = 0..Pi/2} (sin(x))^5*(cos(x))^(2*n-5)). - _Francesco Daddi_, Aug 02 2011
%C A007531 a(n) is the number of functions f:[3] -> [n] that are injective since there are n choices for f(1), (n-1) choices for f(2), and (n-2) choices for f(3). Also, a(n+1) is the number of functions f:[3] -> [n] that are width-2 restricted (that is, the pre-image under f of any element in [n] is of size 2 or less). See "Width-restricted finite functions" link below. - _Dennis P. Walsh_, Mar 01 2012
%C A007531 This sequence is produced by three consecutive triangular numbers t(n-1), t(n-2) and t(n-3) in the expression 2*t(n-1)*(t(n-2)-t(n-3)) for n = 0, 1, 2, ... - _J. M. Bergot_, May 14 2012
%C A007531 For n > 2: A020639(a(n)) = 2; A006530(a(n)) = A093074(n-1). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 04 2012
%C A007531 Number of contact points between equal spheres arranged in a tetrahedron with n - 1 spheres in each edge. - _Ignacio Larrosa Cañestro_, Jan 07 2013
%C A007531 Also for n >= 3, area of Pythagorean triangle in which one side differs from hypotenuse by two units. Consider any Pythagorean triple (2n, n^2-1, n^2+1) where n > 1. The area of such a Pythagorean triangle is n(n^2-1). For n = 2, 3, 4,.. the areas are 6, 24, 60, .... which are the given terms of the series. - _Jayanta Basu_, Apr 11 2013
%C A007531 Cf. A130534 for relations to colored forests, disposition of flags on flagpoles, and colorings of the vertices (chromatic polynomial) of the complete graph K_3. - _Tom Copeland_, Apr 05 2014
%C A007531 Starting with 6, 24, 60, 120, ..., a(n) is the number of permutations of length n>=3 avoiding the partially ordered pattern (POP) {1>2} of length 5. That is, the number of length n permutations having no subsequences of length 5 in which the first element is larger than the second element. - _Sergey Kitaev_, Dec 11 2020
%C A007531 For integer m and positive integer r >= 2, the polynomial a(n) + a(n + m) + a(n + 2*m) + ... + a(n + r*m) in n has its zeros on the vertical line Re(n) = (2 - r*m)/2 in the complex plane. - _Peter Bala_, Jun 02 2024
%C A007531 From _Enrique Navarrete_, Oct 29 2025: (Start)
%C A007531 Number of ternary strings of length n with three 0's and 1's in total, at least one 0 and one 1, and any number of 2's. For example, a(6) = 120 since the strings are the 60 permutations of 011222 and the 60 permutations of 001222.
%C A007531 Also the number of strings of length n defined on {0,1,2,3} with one 0, one 1, one 2, and any number of 3's. (End)
%C A007531 a(g+1) is the number of Weierstrass points on a generic smooth algebraic curve of genus g. - _Harry Richman_, Nov 19 2025
